# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: apache-kudu
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] The core of Apache Hadoop consists of a storage part, known as Hadoop Distributed File System (HDFS), and a processing part which is a MapReduce programming model.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] Hadoop splits files into large blocks and distributes them across nodes in a cluster.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] It then transfers packaged code into nodes to process the data in parallel.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] This approach takes advantage of data locality, where nodes manipulate the data they have access to.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] This allows the dataset to be processed faster and more efficiently than it would be in a more conventional supercomputer architecture that relies on a parallel file system where computation and data are distributed via high-speed networking.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] Apache Hadoop's MapReduce and HDFS components were inspired by Google papers on MapReduce and Google File System.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] The Hadoop framework itself is mostly written in the Java programming language, with some native code in C and command line utilities written as shell scripts.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] Perl language can be easily used with Hadoop Streaming to implement the map and reduce parts of the user's program.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] According to its co-founders, Doug Cutting and Mike Cafarella, the idea of Hadoop was conceived in the Google File System paper that was published in October 2003.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] The concept was extended in the Google paper *"MapReduce: Simplified Data Processing on Large Clusters".* Development started on the Apache Nutch project, but was moved to the new Hadoop subproject in January 2006.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] Doug Cutting, who was working at Yahoo! at the time, named it after his son's toy elephant.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] The initial code that was factored out of Nutch consisted of about 5,000 lines of code for HDFS and about 6,000 lines of code for MapReduce.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] In March 2006, Owen O'Malley was the first committer to add to the Hadoop project; Hadoop 0.1.0 was released in April 2006.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] It continues to evolve through contributions that are being made to the project.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] The first design document for the Hadoop Distributed File System was written by Dhruba Borthakur in 2007.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] Hadoop consists of the *Hadoop Common* package, which provides file system and operating system level abstractions, a MapReduce engine (either MapReduce/MR1 or YARN/MR2) and the Hadoop Distributed File System (HDFS).
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] The Hadoop Common package contains the Java Archive (JAR) files and scripts needed to start Hadoop.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] For effective scheduling of work, every Hadoop-compatible file system should provide location awareness, which is the name of the rack, specifically the network switch where a worker node is.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] Hadoop applications can use this information to execute code on the node where the data is, and, failing that, on the same rack/switch to reduce backbone traffic.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] HDFS uses this method when replicating data for data redundancy across multiple racks.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] This approach reduces the impact of a rack power outage or switch failure; if any of these hardware failures occurs, the data will remain available.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] A small Hadoop cluster includes a single master and multiple worker nodes.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] The master node consists of a Job Tracker, Task Tracker, NameNode, and DataNode.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] A slave or *worker node* acts as both a DataNode and TaskTracker, though it is possible to have data-only and compute-only worker nodes.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] These are normally used only in nonstandard applications.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] Hadoop requires the Java Runtime Environment (JRE) 1.6 or higher.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] The standard startup and shutdown scripts require that Secure Shell (SSH) be set up between nodes in the cluster.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] In a larger cluster, HDFS nodes are managed through a dedicated NameNode server to host the file system index, and a secondary NameNode that can generate snapshots of the namenode's memory structures, thereby preventing file-system corruption and loss of data.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] Similarly, a standalone JobTracker server can manage job scheduling across nodes.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] When Hadoop MapReduce is used with an alternate file system, the NameNode, secondary NameNode, and DataNode architecture of HDFS are replaced by the file-system-specific equivalents.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] The *Hadoop distributed file system* (HDFS) is a distributed, scalable, and portable file system written in Java for the Hadoop framework.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] A Hadoop instance is divided into HDFS and MapReduce.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] HDFS is used for storing the data and MapReduce is used for processing data.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] Top three are Master Services/Daemons/Nodes and bottom two are Slave Services.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] Master Services can communicate with each other and in the same way Slave services can communicate with each other.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] Name Node is a master node and Data node is its corresponding Slave node and can talk with each other.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] Hadoop cluster has nominally a single namenode plus a cluster of datanodes, although redundancy options are available for the namenode due to its criticality.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] Each datanode serves up blocks of data over the network using a block protocol specific to HDFS.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] The file system uses TCP/IP sockets for communication.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] Clients use remote procedure calls (RPC) to communicate with each other.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] HDFS stores large files (typically in the range of gigabytes to terabytes) across multiple machines.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] It achieves reliability by replicating the data across multiple hosts, and hence theoretically does not require redundant array of independent disks (RAID) storage on hosts (but to increase input-output (I/O) performance some RAID configurations are still useful).
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] With the default replication value, 3, data is stored on three nodes: two on the same rack, and one on a different rack.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] Data nodes can talk to each other to rebalance data, to move copies around, and to keep the replication of data high.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] HDFS is not fully POSIX-compliant, because the requirements for a POSIX file-system differ from the target goals of a Hadoop application.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] The trade-off of not having a fully POSIX-compliant file-system is increased performance for data throughput and support for non-POSIX operations such as Append.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] In May 2012, high-availability capabilities were added to HDFS, letting the main metadata server called the NameNode manually fail-over onto a backup.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] The project has also started developing automatic fail-overs.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] The HDFS file system includes a so-called *secondary namenode*, a misleading term that some might incorrectly interpret as a backup namenode when the primary namenode goes offline.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] In fact, the secondary namenode regularly connects with the primary namenode and builds snapshots of the primary namenode's directory information, which the system then saves to local or remote directories.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] These checkpointed images can be used to restart a failed primary namenode without having to replay the entire journal of file-system actions, then to edit the log to create an up-to-date directory structure.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] Because the namenode is the single point for storage and management of metadata, it can become a bottleneck for supporting a huge number of files, especially a large number of small files.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] HDFS Federation, a new addition, aims to tackle this problem to a certain extent by allowing multiple namespaces served by separate namenodes.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] Moreover, there are some issues in HDFS such as small file issues, scalability problems, Single Point of Failure (SPoF), and bottlenecks in huge metadata requests.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] One advantage of using HDFS is data awareness between the job tracker and task tracker.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] The job tracker schedules map or reduce jobs to task trackers with an awareness of the data location.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] For example: if node A contains data (a, b, c) and node X contains data (x, y, z), the job tracker schedules node A to perform map or reduce tasks on (a, b, c) and node X would be scheduled to perform map or reduce tasks on (x, y, z).
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] This reduces the amount of traffic that goes over the network and prevents unnecessary data transfer.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] When Hadoop is used with other file systems, this advantage is not always available.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] This can have a significant impact on job-completion times as demonstrated with data-intensive jobs.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] HDFS was designed for mostly immutable files and may not be suitable for systems requiring concurrent write operations.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] HDFS can be mounted directly with a Filesystem in Userspace (FUSE) virtual file system on Linux and some other Unix systems.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] File access can be achieved through the native Java API, the Thrift API (generates a client in a number of languages e.g.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] C++, Java, Python, PHP, Ruby, Erlang, Perl, Haskell, C#, Cocoa, Smalltalk, and OCaml), the command-line interface, the HDFS-UI web application over HTTP, or via 3rd-party network client libraries.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] HDFS is designed for portability across various hardware platforms and for compatibility with a variety of underlying operating systems.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] The HDFS design introduces portability limitations that result in some performance bottlenecks, since the Java implementation cannot use features that are exclusive to the platform on which HDFS is running.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] Due to its widespread integration into enterprise-level infrastructure, monitoring HDFS performance at scale has become an increasingly important issue.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] Monitoring end-to-end performance requires tracking metrics from datanodes, namenodes, and the underlying operating system.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] There are currently several monitoring platforms to track HDFS performance, including Hortonworks, Cloudera, and Datadog.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] Hadoop works directly with any distributed file system that can be mounted by the underlying operating system by simply using a `file://` URL; however, this comes at a price – the loss of locality.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] To reduce network traffic, Hadoop needs to know which servers are closest to the data, information that Hadoop-specific file system bridges can provide.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] A number of third-party file system bridges have also been written, none of which are currently in Hadoop distributions.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] However, some commercial distributions of Hadoop ship with an alternative file system as the default – specifically IBM and MapR.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] Atop the file systems comes the MapReduce Engine, which consists of one *JobTracker*, to which client applications submit MapReduce jobs.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] The JobTracker pushes work to available *TaskTracker* nodes in the cluster, striving to keep the work as close to the data as possible.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] With a rack-aware file system, the JobTracker knows which node contains the data, and which other machines are nearby.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] If the work cannot be hosted on the actual node where the data resides, priority is given to nodes in the same rack.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] This reduces network traffic on the main backbone network.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] If a TaskTracker fails or times out, that part of the job is rescheduled.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] The TaskTracker on each node spawns a separate Java virtual machine (JVM) process to prevent the TaskTracker itself from failing if the running job crashes its JVM.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] A heartbeat is sent from the TaskTracker to the JobTracker every few minutes to check its status.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] The Job Tracker and TaskTracker status and information is exposed by Jetty and can be viewed from a web browser.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] If one TaskTracker is very slow, it can delay the entire MapReduce job – especially towards the end, when everything can end up waiting for the slowest task.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] With speculative execution enabled, however, a single task can be executed on multiple slave nodes.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] By default Hadoop uses FIFO scheduling, and optionally 5 scheduling priorities to schedule jobs from a work queue.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] In version 0.19 the job scheduler was refactored out of the JobTracker, while adding the ability to use an alternate scheduler (such as the *Fair scheduler* or the *Capacity scheduler*, described next).
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] The fair scheduler was developed by Facebook.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] The goal of the fair scheduler is to provide fast response times for small jobs and quality of service (QoS) for production jobs.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] The fair scheduler has three basic concepts.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] Each pool is assigned a guaranteed minimum share.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] By default, jobs that are uncategorized go into a default pool.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] Pools have to specify the minimum number of map slots, reduce slots, as well as a limit on the number of running jobs.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] The capacity scheduler was developed by Yahoo.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] The capacity scheduler supports several features that are similar to those of the fair scheduler.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] Free resources are allocated to queues beyond their total capacity.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] Within a queue, a job with a high level of priority has access to the queue's resources.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] There is no preemption once a job is running.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] The biggest difference between Hadoop 1 and Hadoop 2 is the addition of YARN (Yet Another Resource Negotiator), which replaced the MapReduce engine in the first version of Hadoop.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] YARN strives to allocate resources to various applications effectively.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] It runs two daemons, which take care of two different tasks: the *resource manager*, which does job tracking and resource allocation to applications, the *application master*, which monitors progress of the execution.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] There are important features provided by Hadoop 3.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] For example, while there is one single *namenode* in Hadoop 2, Hadoop 3, enables having multiple name nodes, which solves the single point of failure problem.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] In Hadoop 3, there are containers working in principle of Docker, which reduces time spent on application development.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] One of the biggest changes is that Hadoop 3 decreases storage overhead with erasure coding.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] Also, Hadoop 3 permits usage of GPU hardware within the cluster, which is a very substantial benefit to execute deep learning algorithms on a Hadoop cluster.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] The HDFS is not restricted to MapReduce jobs.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] It can be used for other applications, many of which are under development at Apache.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] The list includes the HBase database, the Apache Mahout machine learning system, and the Apache Hive data warehouse.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] Theoretically, Hadoop could be used for any workload that is batch-oriented rather than real-time, is very data-intensive, and benefits from parallel processing.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] It can also be used to complement a real-time system, such as lambda architecture, Apache Storm, Flink, and Spark Streaming.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] Inc. launched what they claimed was the world's largest Hadoop production application.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] Search Webmap is a Hadoop application that runs on a Linux cluster with more than 10,000 cores and produced data that was used in every Yahoo! web search query.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] There are multiple Hadoop clusters at Yahoo! and no HDFS file systems or MapReduce jobs are split across multiple data centers.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] Every Hadoop cluster node bootstraps the Linux image, including the Hadoop distribution.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] Work that the clusters perform is known to include the index calculations for the Yahoo! search engine.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] In June 2009, Yahoo! made the source code of its Hadoop version available to the open-source community.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] In 2010, Facebook claimed that they had the largest Hadoop cluster in the world with 21 PB of storage.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] In June 2012, they announced the data had grown to 100 PB and later that year they announced that the data was growing by roughly half a PB per day.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] As of 2013, Hadoop adoption had become widespread: more than half of the Fortune 50 companies used Hadoop.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] Influential papers on the birth, growth, and curation of Hadoop and big data processing include: Jeffrey Dean, Sanjay Ghemawat (2004) MapReduce: Simplified Data Processing on Large Clusters, Google.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] This paper inspired Doug Cutting to develop an open-source implementation of the Map-Reduce framework.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-hadoop] He named it Hadoop, after his son's toy elephant.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-impala] Apache Impala is a query engine that runs on Apache Hadoop.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-impala] The project was announced in October 2012 with a public beta test distribution and became generally available in May 2013.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-impala] Impala brings scalable parallel database technology to Hadoop, enabling users to issue low-latency SQL queries to data stored in HDFS and Apache HBase without requiring data movement or transformation.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-impala] Impala is integrated with Hadoop to use the same file and data formats, metadata, security and resource management frameworks used by MapReduce, Apache Hive, Apache Pig and other Hadoop software.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-impala] Impala is promoted for analysts and data scientists to perform analytics on data stored in Hadoop via SQL or business intelligence tools.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-impala] The result is that large-scale data processing (via MapReduce) and interactive queries can be done on the same system using the same data and metadata – removing the need to migrate data sets into specialized systems and/or proprietary formats simply to perform analysis.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-impala] In early 2013, a column-oriented file format called Parquet was announced for architectures including Impala.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-impala] In December 2013, Amazon Web Services announced support for Impala.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-impala] In early 2014, MapR added support for Impala.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-impala] In 2015, another format called Kudu was announced, which Cloudera proposed to donate to the Apache Software Foundation along with Impala.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-impala] Impala graduated to an Apache Top-Level Project (TLP) on 28 November 2017.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-kudu] The open source project to build Apache Kudu began as internal project at Cloudera.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-kudu] The first version Apache Kudu 1.0 was released 19 September 2016.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-kudu] Kudu was designed and optimized for OLAP workloads.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-kudu] Like HBase, it is a real-time store that supports key-indexed record lookup and mutation.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-kudu] Kudu differs from HBase since Kudu's datamodel is a more traditional relational model, while HBase is schemaless.
[src:apache-kudu/apache-kudu] Kudu's "on-disk representation is truly columnar and follows an entirely different storage design than HBase/Bigtable".
[src:apache-kudu/column-oriented-dbms] The choice of data orientation is a trade-off and an architectural decision in databases, query engines, and numerical simulations.
[src:apache-kudu/column-oriented-dbms] As a result of these tradeoffs, row-oriented formats are more commonly used in online transaction processing (OLTP) and column-oriented formats are more commonly used in online analytical processing (OLAP).
[src:apache-kudu/column-oriented-dbms] Examples of column-oriented formats include Apache ORC, Apache Parquet, Apache Arrow, formats used by BigQuery, Amazon Redshift and Snowflake.
[src:apache-kudu/column-oriented-dbms] Predominant examples of row-oriented formats include CSV, formats used in most relational databases (Oracle, MySQL etc.), the in-memory format of Apache Spark, and Apache Avro.
[src:apache-kudu/column-oriented-dbms] Tabular data is two dimensional — data is modeled as rows and columns.
[src:apache-kudu/column-oriented-dbms] However, computer systems represent data in a linear memory model, both in-disk and in-memory.
[src:apache-kudu/column-oriented-dbms] Therefore, a table in a linear memory model requires mapping its two-dimensional scheme into a one-dimensional space.
[src:apache-kudu/column-oriented-dbms] Data orientation is to the decision taken in this mapping.
[src:apache-kudu/column-oriented-dbms] There are two prominent mappings: row-oriented and column-oriented.
[src:apache-kudu/column-oriented-dbms] I.e. each row of the table is located one after the other.
[src:apache-kudu/column-oriented-dbms] In this orientation, values in the same row are close in space (e.g. similar address in an addressable space).
[src:apache-kudu/column-oriented-dbms] I.e. each column of the table is located one after the other.
[src:apache-kudu/column-oriented-dbms] In this orientation, values on the same column are close in space (e.g. similar address in an addressable space).
[src:apache-kudu/column-oriented-dbms] See list of column-oriented DBMSes for more examples.
[src:apache-kudu/column-oriented-dbms] Data orientation is an important architectural decision of systems handling data because it results in important tradeoffs in performance and storage.
[src:apache-kudu/column-oriented-dbms] Below are selected dimensions of this tradeoff.
[src:apache-kudu/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast random access of rows.
[src:apache-kudu/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast random access of columns.
[src:apache-kudu/column-oriented-dbms] In both cases, this is the result of fewer page or cache misses when accessing the data.
[src:apache-kudu/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast insertion of a new row.
[src:apache-kudu/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast insertion of a new column.
[src:apache-kudu/column-oriented-dbms] This dimension is an important reason why row-oriented formats are more commonly used in online transaction processing (OLTP), as it results in faster transactions in comparison to column-oriented.
[src:apache-kudu/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast access under a filter.
[src:apache-kudu/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast access under a projection.
[src:apache-kudu/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast analytics operations.
[src:apache-kudu/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of being able to leverage SIMD instructions.
[src:apache-kudu/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from smaller uncompressed size.
[src:apache-kudu/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of the possibility that this orientation offers to represent certain data types with dedicated encodings.
[src:apache-kudu/column-oriented-dbms] For example, a table of 128 rows with a Boolean column requires 128 bytes in a row-oriented format (one byte per Boolean) but 128 bits (16 bytes) in a column-oriented format (via a bitmap).
[src:apache-kudu/column-oriented-dbms] Another example is the use of run-length encoding to encode a column.
[src:apache-kudu/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from smaller compressed size.
[src:apache-kudu/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of a higher homogeneity within a column than within multiple rows.
[src:apache-kudu/column-oriented-dbms] Because both orientations represent the same data, it is possible to convert a row-oriented dataset to a column-oriented dataset and vice versa at the expense of compute.
[src:apache-kudu/column-oriented-dbms] In particular, advanced query engines often leverage each orientation's advantages, and convert from one orientation to the other as part of their execution.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] Kudu is a distributed columnar storage engine optimized for OLAP workloads.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] Kudu runs on commodity hardware, is horizontally scalable, and supports highly available operation.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] By combining all of these properties, Kudu targets support for families of applications that are difficult or impossible to implement using Hadoop storage technologies, while it is compatible with most of the data processing frameworks in the Hadoop ecosystem.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] For more information about these and other scenarios, see Example Use Cases.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] Impala supports creating, altering, and dropping tables using Kudu as the persistence layer.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] The tables follow the same internal / external approach as other tables in Impala, allowing for flexible data ingestion and querying.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] Data can be inserted into Kudu tables in Impala using the same syntax as any other Impala table like those using HDFS or HBase for persistence.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] Impala supports the `UPDATE` and `DELETE` SQL commands to modify existing data in a Kudu table row-by-row or as a batch.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] The syntax of the SQL commands is chosen to be as compatible as possible with existing standards.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] In addition to simple `DELETE` or `UPDATE` commands, you can specify complex joins with a `FROM` clause in a subquery.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] Similar to partitioning of tables in Hive, Kudu allows you to dynamically pre-split tables by hash or range into a predefined number of tablets, in order to distribute writes and queries evenly across your cluster.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] You can partition by any number of primary key columns, by any number of hashes, and an optional list of split rows.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] To achieve the highest possible performance on modern hardware, the Kudu client used by Impala parallelizes scans across multiple tablets.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] Where possible, Impala pushes down predicate evaluation to Kudu, so that predicates are evaluated as close as possible to the data.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] Query performance is comparable to Parquet in many workloads.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] For more details regarding querying data stored in Kudu using Impala, please refer to the Impala documentation.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] A columnar data store stores data in strongly-typed columns.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] With a proper design, it is superior for analytical or data warehousing workloads for several reasons.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] For analytical queries, you can read a single column, or a portion of that column, while ignoring other columns.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] This means you can fulfill your query while reading a minimal number of blocks on disk.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] With a row-based store, you need to read the entire row, even if you only return values from a few columns.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] Because a given column contains only one type of data, pattern-based compression can be orders of magnitude more efficient than compressing mixed data types, which are used in row-based solutions.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] Combined with the efficiencies of reading data from columns, compression allows you to fulfill your query while reading even fewer blocks from disk.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] A *table* is where your data is stored in Kudu.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] A table has a schema and a totally ordered primary key.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] A table is split into segments called tablets.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] A *tablet* is a contiguous segment of a table, similar to a *partition* in other data storage engines or relational databases.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] A given tablet is replicated on multiple tablet servers, and at any given point in time, one of these replicas is considered the leader tablet.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] Any replica can service reads, and writes require consensus among the set of tablet servers serving the tablet.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] A *tablet server* stores and serves tablets to clients.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] For a given tablet, one tablet server acts as a leader, and the others act as follower replicas of that tablet.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] Only leaders service write requests, while leaders or followers each service read requests.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] Leaders are elected using Raft Consensus Algorithm.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] One tablet server can serve multiple tablets, and one tablet can be served by multiple tablet servers.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] The *master* keeps track of all the tablets, tablet servers, the Catalog Table, and other metadata related to the cluster.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] At a given point in time, there can only be one acting master (the leader).
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] If the current leader disappears, a new master is elected using Raft Consensus Algorithm.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] The master also coordinates metadata operations for clients.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] For example, when creating a new table, the client internally sends the request to the master.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] The master writes the metadata for the new table into the catalog table, and coordinates the process of creating tablets on the tablet servers.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] All the master’s data is stored in a tablet, which can be replicated to all the other candidate masters.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] Tablet servers heartbeat to the master at a set interval (the default is once per second).
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] Kudu uses the Raft consensus algorithm as a means to guarantee fault-tolerance and consistency, both for regular tablets and for master data.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] Through Raft, multiple replicas of a tablet elect a *leader*, which is responsible for accepting and replicating writes to *follower* replicas.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] Once a write is persisted in a majority of replicas it is acknowledged to the client.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] A given group of `N` replicas (usually 3 or 5) is able to accept writes with at most `(N - 1)/2` faulty replicas.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] The *catalog table* is the central location for metadata of Kudu.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] It stores information about tables and tablets.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] The catalog table may not be read or written directly.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] Instead, it is accessible only via metadata operations exposed in the client API.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] the list of existing tablets, which tablet servers have replicas of each tablet, the tablet’s current state, and start and end keys.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] Kudu replicates operations, not on-disk data.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] This is referred to as *logical replication*, as opposed to *physical replication*.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] The following diagram shows a Kudu cluster with three masters and multiple tablet servers, each serving multiple tablets.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] It illustrates how Raft consensus is used to allow for both leaders and followers for both the masters and tablet servers.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] In addition, a tablet server can be a leader for some tablets, and a follower for others.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] Leaders are shown in gold, while followers are shown in blue.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] A common challenge in data analysis is one where new data arrives rapidly and constantly, and the same data needs to be available in near real time for reads, scans, and updates.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] Kudu offers the powerful combination of fast inserts and updates with efficient columnar scans to enable real-time analytics use cases on a single storage layer.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] A time-series schema is one in which data points are organized and keyed according to the time at which they occurred.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] This can be useful for investigating the performance of metrics over time or attempting to predict future behavior based on past data.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] For instance, time-series customer data might be used both to store purchase click-stream history and to predict future purchases, or for use by a customer support representative.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] While these different types of analysis are occurring, inserts and mutations may also be occurring individually and in bulk, and become available immediately to read workloads.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] Kudu can handle all of these access patterns simultaneously in a scalable and efficient manner.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] Kudu is a good fit for time-series workloads for several reasons.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] With Kudu’s support for hash-based partitioning, combined with its native support for compound row keys, it is simple to set up a table spread across many servers without the risk of "hotspotting" that is commonly observed when range partitioning is used.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] Kudu’s columnar storage engine is also beneficial in this context, because many time-series workloads read only a few columns, as opposed to the whole row.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] In the past, you might have needed to use multiple data stores to handle different data access patterns.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] This practice adds complexity to your application and operations, and duplicates your data, doubling (or worse) the amount of storage required.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] Kudu can handle all of these access patterns natively and efficiently, without the need to off-load work to other data stores.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] Data scientists often develop predictive learning models from large sets of data.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] The model and the data may need to be updated or modified often as the learning takes place or as the situation being modeled changes.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] In addition, the scientist may want to change one or more factors in the model to see what happens over time.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] Updating a large set of data stored in files in HDFS is resource-intensive, as each file needs to be completely rewritten.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] In Kudu, updates happen in near real time.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] The scientist can tweak the value, re-run the query, and refresh the graph in seconds or minutes, rather than hours or days.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] In addition, batch or incremental algorithms can be run across the data at any time, with near-real-time results.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] Companies generate data from multiple sources and store it in a variety of systems and formats.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] For instance, some of your data may be stored in Kudu, some in a traditional RDBMS, and some in files in HDFS.
[src:apache-kudu/index-page] You can access and query all of these sources and formats using Impala, without the need to change your legacy systems.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Kudu tables have a structured data model similar to tables in a traditional RDBMS.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Schema design is critical for achieving the best performance and operational stability from Kudu.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Every workload is unique, and there is no single schema design that is best for every table.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] This document outlines effective schema design philosophies for Kudu, paying particular attention to where they differ from approaches used for traditional RDBMS schemas.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] At a high level, there are three concerns when creating Kudu tables: column design, primary key design, and partitioning design.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Of these, only partitioning will be a new concept for those familiar with traditional non-distributed relational databases.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] The final sections discuss altering the schema of an existing table, and known limitations with regard to schema design.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] The perfect schema depends on the characteristics of your data, what you need to do with it, and the topology of your cluster.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Schema design is the single most important thing within your control to maximize the performance of your Kudu cluster.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] A Kudu Table consists of one or more columns, each with a defined type.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Columns that are not part of the primary key may be nullable.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Kudu takes advantage of strongly-typed columns and a columnar on-disk storage format to provide efficient encoding and serialization.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] To make the most of these features, columns should be specified as the appropriate type, rather than simulating a 'schemaless' table using string or binary columns for data which may otherwise be structured.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] In addition to encoding, Kudu allows compression to be specified on a per-column basis.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] The `decimal` type is a numeric data type with fixed scale and precision suitable for financial and other arithmetic calculations where the imprecise representation and rounding behavior of `float` and `double` make those types impractical.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] The `decimal` type is also useful for integers larger than int64 and cases with fractional values in a primary key.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] The `decimal` type is a parameterized type that takes precision and scale type attributes.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Kudu stores each value in as few bytes as possible depending on the precision specified for the decimal column.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] For that reason it is not advised to just use the highest precision possible for convenience.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Doing so could negatively impact performance, memory and storage.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] The `varchar` type is a UTF-8 encoded string (up to 64KB uncompressed) with a fixed maximum character length.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] This type is especially useful when migrating from or integrating with legacy systems that support the `varchar` type.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] If a maximum character length is not required the `string` type should be used instead.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] The `varchar` type is a parameterized type that takes a length attribute.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Each column in a Kudu table can be created with an encoding, based on the type of the column.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] For example, `int32` values are stored as fixed-size 32-bit little-endian integers.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] A block of values is rearranged to store the most significant bit of every value, followed by the second most significant bit of every value, and so on.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Bitshuffle encoding is a good choice for columns that have many repeated values, or values that change by small amounts when sorted by primary key.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] The bitshuffle project has a good overview of performance and use cases.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] A dictionary of unique values is built, and each column value is encoded as its corresponding index in the dictionary.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Dictionary encoding is effective for columns with low cardinality.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] If the column values of a given row set are unable to be compressed because the number of unique values is too high, Kudu will transparently fall back to plain encoding for that row set.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Common prefixes are compressed in consecutive column values.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Prefix encoding can be effective for values that share common prefixes, or the first column of the primary key, since rows are sorted by primary key within tablets.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Kudu allows per-column compression using the `LZ4`, `Snappy`, or `zlib` compression codecs.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] By default, columns that are Bitshuffle-encoded are inherently compressed with LZ4 compression.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Otherwise, columns are stored uncompressed.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Consider using compression if reducing storage space is more important than raw scan performance.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Every data set will compress differently, but in general LZ4 is the most performant codec, while `zlib` will compress to the smallest data sizes.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Bitshuffle-encoded columns are automatically compressed using LZ4, so it is not recommended to apply additional compression on top of this encoding.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Every Kudu table must declare a primary key comprised of one or more columns.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Like an RDBMS primary key, the Kudu primary key enforces a uniqueness constraint.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Attempting to insert a row with the same primary key values as an existing row will result in a duplicate key error.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Primary key columns must be non-nullable, and may not be a boolean, float or double type.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Once set during table creation, the set of columns in the primary key may not be altered.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Unlike an RDBMS, Kudu does not provide an explicit auto-incrementing column feature, so the application must always provide the full primary key during insert.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Columns which do not satisfy the uniqueness constraint can still be used as primary keys, by specifying them as non-unique primary keys.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Row delete and update operations must also specify the full primary key of the row to be changed.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Kudu does not natively support range deletes or updates.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] The primary key values of a column may not be updated after the row is inserted.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] However, the row may be deleted and re-inserted with the updated value.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] As with many traditional relational databases, Kudu’s primary key is in a clustered index.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] All rows within a tablet are sorted by its primary key.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] When scanning Kudu rows, use equality or range predicates on primary key columns to efficiently find the rows.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] While specifying columns as non-unique primary key, Kudu internally creates an auto-incrementing column.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] The specified columns and the auto-incrementing column form the effective primary key.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Non-unique primary key columns must be non-nullable, and may not be a boolean, float or double type.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Once set during table creation, the set of columns in the non-unique primary key and the auto-incrementing column can not be altered.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] For inserts, one has to provide values for the non-unique primary key columns without specifying the values for auto-incrementing column.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] The auto-incrementing column is populated on the server side automatically.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] For updates/deletes the full set of key columns is necessary.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] One has to perform a scan before update/delete operation to get the auto-incrementing value.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Upsert operation is not supported on tables with non-unique primary key.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] The non-unique primary key values of a column may not be updated after the row is inserted.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] However, the row may be deleted and re-inserted with the updated value, moreover a new auto-incrementing counter value is assigned during insertion for auto-incrementing column.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Restoring tables with non-unique primary keys is not supported currently.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] For more details on how to use non-unique primary key, please check the examples folder.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] This section discuss a primary key design consideration for timeseries use cases where the primary key is a timestamp, or the first column of the primary key is a timestamp.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Each time a row is inserted into a Kudu table, Kudu looks up the primary key in the primary key index storage to check whether that primary key is already present in the table.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] If the primary key exists in the table, a "duplicate key" error is returned.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] In the typical case where data is being inserted at the current time as it arrives from the data source, only a small range of primary keys are "hot".
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] So, each of these "check for presence" operations is very fast.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] It hits the cached primary key storage in memory and doesn’t require going to disk.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] In the case when you load historical data, which is called "backfilling", from an offline data source, each row that is inserted is likely to hit a cold area of the primary key index which is not resident in memory and will cause one or more HDD disk seeks.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] For example, in a normal ingestion case where Kudu sustains a few million inserts per second, the "backfill" use case might sustain only a few thousand inserts per second.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] In order to provide scalability, Kudu tables are partitioned into units called tablets, and distributed across many tablet servers.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] A row always belongs to a single tablet.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] The method of assigning rows to tablets is determined by the partitioning of the table, which is set during table creation.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Choosing a partitioning strategy requires understanding the data model and the expected workload of a table.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] For write-heavy workloads, it is important to design the partitioning such that writes are spread across tablets in order to avoid overloading a single tablet.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] For workloads involving many short scans, where the overhead of contacting remote servers dominates, performance can be improved if all of the data for the scan is located in the same tablet.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Understanding these fundamental trade-offs is central to designing an effective partition schema.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Kudu provides two types of partitioning: range partitioning and hash partitioning.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Tables may also have multilevel partitioning, which combines range and hash partitioning, or multiple instances of hash partitioning.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Range partitioning distributes rows using a totally-ordered range partition key.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Each partition is assigned a contiguous segment of the range partition keyspace.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] The key must be comprised of a subset of the primary key columns.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] If the range partition columns match the primary key columns, then the range partition key of a row will equal its primary key.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] In range partitioned tables without hash partitioning, each range partition will correspond to exactly one tablet.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] The initial set of range partitions is specified during table creation as a set of partition bounds and split rows.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] For each bound, a range partition will be created in the table.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Each split will divide a range partition in two.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] If no partition bounds are specified, then the table will default to a single partition covering the entire key space (unbounded below and above).
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Range partitions must always be non-overlapping, and split rows must fall within a range partition.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Kudu allows range partitions to be dynamically added and removed from a table at runtime, without affecting the availability of other partitions.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Removing a partition will delete the tablets belonging to the partition, as well as the data contained in them.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Subsequent inserts into the dropped partition will fail.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] New partitions can be added, but they must not overlap with any existing range partitions.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Kudu allows dropping and adding any number of range partitions in a single transactional alter table operation.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Dynamically adding and dropping range partitions is particularly useful for time series use cases.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] As time goes on, range partitions can be added to cover upcoming time ranges.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] For example, a table storing an event log could add a month-wide partition just before the start of each month in order to hold the upcoming events.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Old range partitions can be dropped in order to efficiently remove historical data, as necessary.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Hash partitioning distributes rows by hash value into one of many buckets.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] In single-level hash partitioned tables, each bucket will correspond to exactly one tablet.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] The number of buckets is set during table creation.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Typically the primary key columns are used as the columns to hash, but as with range partitioning, any subset of the primary key columns can be used.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Hash partitioning is an effective strategy when ordered access to the table is not needed.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Hash partitioning is effective for spreading writes randomly among tablets, which helps mitigate hot-spotting and uneven tablet sizes.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Kudu allows a table to combine multiple levels of partitioning on a single table.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Zero or more hash partition levels can be combined with an optional range partition level.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] The only additional constraint on multilevel partitioning beyond the constraints of the individual partition types, is that multiple levels of hash partitions must not hash the same columns.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] When used correctly, multilevel partitioning can retain the benefits of the individual partitioning types, while reducing the downsides of each.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] The total number of tablets in a multilevel partitioned table is the product of the number of partitions in each level.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] As of 1.17, Kudu supports range-specific hash schema for tables.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] It’s now possible to add ranges with their own unique hash schema independent of the table-wide hash schema.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] This can be done while creating or altering the table.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] This feature helps mitigate potential hotspotting as more buckets can be added for a hash schema of a range that expects more workload.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Kudu scans will automatically skip scanning entire partitions when it can be determined that the partition can be entirely filtered by the scan predicates.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] To prune hash partitions, the scan must include equality predicates on every hashed column.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] To prune range partitions, the scan must include equality or range predicates on the range partitioned columns.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Scans on multilevel partitioned tables can take advantage of partition pruning on any of the levels independently.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] To illustrate the factors and trade-offs associated with designing a partitioning strategy for a table, we will walk through some different partitioning scenarios.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] A natural way to partition the `metrics` table is to range partition on the `time` column.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Let’s assume that we want to have a partition per year, and the table will hold data for 2014, 2015, and 2016.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] There are at least two ways that the table could be partitioned: with unbounded range partitions, or with bounded range partitions.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] The image above shows the two ways the `metrics` table can be range partitioned on the `time` column.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] In the first example (in blue), the default range partition bounds are used, with splits at `2015-01-01` and `2016-01-01`.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] This results in three tablets: the first containing values before 2015, the second containing values in the year 2015, and the third containing values after 2016.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] The first example has unbounded lower and upper range partitions, while the second example includes bounds.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Each of the range partition examples above allows time-bounded scans to prune partitions falling outside of the scan’s time bound.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] This can greatly improve performance when there are many partitions.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] When writing, both examples suffer from potential hot-spotting issues.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Because metrics tend to always be written at the current time, most writes will go into a single range partition.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] The second example is more flexible than the first, because it allows range partitions for future years to be added to the table.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] In the first example, all writes for times after `2016-01-01` will fall into the last partition, so the partition may eventually become too large for a single tablet server to handle.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Another way of partitioning the `metrics` table is to hash partition on the `host` and `metric` columns.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] In the example above, the `metrics` table is hash partitioned on the `host` and `metric` columns into four buckets.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Unlike the range partitioning example earlier, this partitioning strategy will spread writes over all tablets in the table evenly, which helps overall write throughput.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Scans over a specific host and metric can take advantage of partition pruning by specifying equality predicates, reducing the number of scanned tablets to one.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] One issue to be careful of with a pure hash partitioning strategy, is that tablets could grow indefinitely as more and more data is inserted into the table.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Eventually tablets will become too big for an individual tablet server to hold.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] The previous examples showed how the `metrics` table could be range partitioned on the `time` column, or hash partitioned on the `host` and `metric` columns.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Hash partitioning is good at maximizing write throughput, while range partitioning avoids issues of unbounded tablet growth.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Both strategies can take advantage of partition pruning to optimize scans in different scenarios.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Using multilevel partitioning, it is possible to combine the two strategies in order to gain the benefits of both, while minimizing the drawbacks of each.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] In the example above, range partitioning on the `time` column is combined with hash partitioning on the `host` and `metric` columns.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] This strategy can be thought of as having two dimensions of partitioning: one for the hash level and one for the range level.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Writes into this table at the current time will be parallelized up to the number of hash buckets, in this case 4.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Reads can take advantage of time bound **and** specific host and metric predicates to prune partitions.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] New range partitions can be added, which results in creating 4 additional tablets (as if a new column were added to the diagram).
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Kudu can support any number of hash partitioning levels in the same table, as long as the levels have no hashed columns in common.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] In the example above, the table is hash partitioned on `host` into 4 buckets, and hash partitioned on `metric` into 3 buckets, resulting in 12 tablets.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Although writes will tend to be spread among all tablets when using this strategy, it is slightly more prone to hot-spotting than when hash partitioning over multiple independent columns, since all values for an individual host or metric will always belong to a single tablet.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Scans can take advantage of equality predicates on the `host` and `metric` columns separately to prune partitions.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Multiple levels of hash partitioning can also be combined with range partitioning, which logically adds another dimension of partitioning.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Multiple alteration steps can be combined in a single transactional operation.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Kudu currently has some known limitations that may factor into schema design.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] By default, Kudu will not permit the creation of tables with more than 300 columns.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] We recommend schema designs that use fewer columns for best performance.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] No individual cell may be larger than 64KB before encoding or compression.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] The cells making up a composite key are limited to a total of 16KB after the internal composite-key encoding done by Kudu.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Inserting rows not conforming to these limitations will result in errors being returned to the client.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Although individual cells may be up to 64KB, and Kudu supports up to 300 columns, it is recommended that no single row be larger than a few hundred KB.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Identifiers such as table and column names must be valid UTF-8 sequences and no longer than 256 bytes.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Kudu does not allow you to update the primary key columns of a row.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Kudu does not allow you to alter the primary key columns after table creation.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Kudu does not allow you to change how a table is partitioned after creation, with the exception of adding or dropping range partitions.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Kudu does not allow the type of a column to be altered.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Partitions cannot be split or merged after table creation.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] The disk space occupied by a deleted row is only reclaimable via compaction, and only when the deletion’s age exceeds the "tablet history maximum age" (controlled by the `--tablet_history_max_age_sec` flag).
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] Furthermore, Kudu currently only schedules compactions in order to improve read/write performance; a tablet will never be compacted purely to reclaim disk space.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] As such, range partitioning should be used when it is expected that large swaths of rows will be discarded.
[src:apache-kudu/schema-design] With range partitioning, individual partitions may be dropped to discard data and reclaim disk space.
